#
DREADLORD (Sub-Class of: Fighter)
===========================================================================
Dreadlords, also knows as the Eyeless, are the warlords of the undead. They
are the result of a dark and terrible ritual performed on a person. The end
of the ritual is marked by the person sacrificing his eyes by clawing them
out and then giving his life to the Dark Lords. If he is deemed worthy he
will once again rise, this time as an undead, a Dreadlord. If he is not
deemed worthy he has an eternity in the pits of hell to ponder his
arrogance. The loss of their eyes does not, as many believe, encumber the
Eyeless in any way. Instead they are giving a seventh sense by which they
can perceive their surroundings. This also makes them immune against
blindness and other things that would normally affect eyesight, such as
daylight and darkness, yet sensitive to extremes of heat. A Dreadlord is a
feared fighter, a master in the use of two-handed weapons, spreading the
taint of the dead as they fight. Even their blood can kill. They are also
trained in the art of leading and are deadly while commanding a force.  

Allowable races:        Lich, Vampire, Shade.
Equipment usage:        Like all classes on Duris, Dreadlords have their
                        own item restrictions. They can use most heavy
                        armor and weapons but are more limited in using
                        magical items.
Innate Abilities:	Acid Blood, Inability to Blind.

===========================================================================
See also: "ACID BLOOD", SKILL_DREADLORD

#
"DREAM TRAVEL" (Spell)
===========================================================================
Area of effect: Caster and player(s)
Aggressive:     No
Cumulative:     No
Duration:       Instantaneous
Type of spell:  Teleportation

The spell dream travel is a VERY powerful teleportation type spell. Casting
this spell on a player causes the caster to fall asleep and dream of his 
destination and when the caster wakes up he has arrived in most cases at
whom he dreamed of. If the caster casts this spell on themselves every
one in their group not in combat that has consented the caster will 
fall into a deep sleep causing them to dream of the caster and after 
wakening they will be in the same room as the caster.

syntax: cast 'dream travel' playername -to travel to any player on your
        side of the race wars.

	cast 'dream travel' self or me -to cause all consented group
        members to travel to your location. 
===========================================================================

#
DROP (Command)
===========================================================================
Syntax:        drop <object>

If you find you no longer need an item, or if you accidentally pick up the
wrong one, you can drop it on the ground. Due to the fact that leaving
items lying around is messy and causes a lot of game overhead, we suggest
that you drop, bury, hide or sell objects that you do not wish to keep.

If you feel like getting rid of all the items you are currently
carrying, you may use the command "drop all."

NOTE: Items left on the ground will not be there after reboots.
===========================================================================
See also: GET, TAKE, BURY, HIDE, SELL

#
"DROW ELF" (General Information)
===========================================================================
Living far beneath the surface, deep within the bowels of the Underdark,
drow elves are a swift-moving, crafty, remorselessly wicked people ruled by
a society of priestesses who serve the demonic Spider Queen, Lloth. The
drow are an extremely intelligent race, and their abilities and ambition
are feared and loathed by races throughout the Realms, particularly grey
elves, their distant cousins and blood enemies.

Because of the length of time they spend below the surface, drow are hurt
by the natural light of the sun and the light of fire. To compensate, they
have permanent ultravision, allowing them to see in total darkness.
However, they seldom travel to the surface, and never during the daytime.
Drow tend to be weaker and frailer than humans, but are better in most
other areas. Drow are somewhat resistant to magical attacks.

Class list:       Warrior, Cleric, Sorcerer, Conjurer, Necromancer, Thief,
                  Assassin, Bard, Reaver.
Innate abilities: levitate, faerie fire, ultravision, fireball, globe
                  of darkness, mass dispel.

Warning: As one of the eight evil races on Duris, the drow are extremely
difficult to play and face many hardships. Their hometown has been
specifically designed to make life hell and death waits around every
corner. Drow will most certainly encounter situations that would be deemed
"unfair" to any of the surface races. We did this to create a new challenge
for those advanced players who have "beaten" the challenge of life on the
surface world and are looking for something more difficult. You should NOT
play a drow unless you are a *very* advanced player and are used to the
Duris style of MUDding, or are willing to face the hardships without
complaint, as it will NOT be easy.
===========================================================================
See also: RACES, "GREY ELF", LEVITATE, DARKNESS, "FAERIE FIRE",
           ULTRAVISION, INNATE

#
DRUID (Sub-Class of: Priest)
===========================================================================
Druids are powerful priestly types that concentrate their discipline toward
the betterment of nature and world preservation. They generally worship 
deities of the forest and of nature and will dispatch anyone attempting to 
desecrate or destroy a forest. Although their spell-like powers are 
primarily defensive in nature, they do command some very potent offensive 
magic once they attain the higher circles.

Druids have shunned the pantheon of gods and allied themselves with the 
natural world instead. They must 'commune' with their surroundings to 
derive the natural essence that is necessary for their spells. This essence
is most abundant in the untamed wilds.

The Druid class does not pray for spells like other "priests", instead,
their spell slots refill automatically as long as they are not fighting,
casting, unconscious, etc. It is unnecessary to designate a specific array
of spells to memorize (see below). To offset this, the rate of spell 
recovery depends on the availability of natural essence in the Druid's 
surroundings. This essence is readily available in forests, but becomes 
more scarce on other types of terrain, especially indoors. Furthermore,
the essence is automatically channeled into the lowest circle that is not 
completely full before it is channeled into higher circles, so it is 
impossible to prioritize what spells to regain first. Overall, Druids have 
slower, more constant spell recovery.

Allowable races:        Human, Grey Elf, Half-Elf, Centaur

Innate abilities:       Shapechange, Charm Animal, Plane Shift

Equipment Usage:        Druids fall under the Priest classification of
                        item restriction. This means they are generally 
                        restricted to the use of non-edged weapons. Some 
                        exceptions are made depending on which deity the 
                        druid worships. They can wear almost all types of 
                        armor, and are only mildly restricted in usage of 
                        certain miscellaneous magical items.  
===========================================================================
See also: SKILL_DRUID, COMMUNE

#
"DUAL WIELD" (Skill)
===========================================================================
"Dual Wield" allows you to wield a primary AND secondary weapon and to use
both to hit your opponent during combat. This, in effect, gives you an  
extra attack per round. The success of the attack depends on your
proficiency in that particular area.

Note: While it is possible for other classes to wield two weapons at once,
they cannot practice this skill and the chances of their hitting an opponent
with a secondary weapon is very unlikely.
===========================================================================

#
"DUERGAR DWARF"
===========================================================================
The duergar are an evil race of gray dwarves that live deep under the
surface of the world, within the depths of the Underdark.  Extremely
cunning and wicked creatures, duergar are known for their deceit and
evil ways.  They hate all other races, except for the drow, with whom
they have grudging trade relations.  They are mortal enemies of the
mountain dwarves.

Duergar are inordinately sturdy and strong, and have permanent
ultravision.  Like the drow, duergar are hurt by natural daylight and
fire, and therefore travel to the surface rarely.

Duergar class list:  Warrior, Cleric, Thief, Assassin, Mercenary.

Duergar stats:  Duergar are stronger and hardier than humans, and somewhat
                more dexterous, but tend to be less intelligent and agile.

Duergar innate abilities:  invisibility, strength, ultravision, UD-sneak,
			   enlarge, hide

&+RWarning:&n  As one of the eight evil races on Duris, the duergar
are extremely difficult to play and face many hardships.  Their
hometown has been specifically designed to make life hell, and death
waits around every corner.  Duergar will most certainly encounter
situations that would be deemed "unfair" to any of the surface races.
We did this to create a new challenge for those advanced players who
have "beaten" the challenge of life on the surface world and are
looking for something more difficult.  You should NOT play a duergar
unless you are a *very* advanced player and are used to the Duris
style of MUDding, or are willing to face the hardships without
complaint, as it is NOT easy.
===========================================================================
See also: RACES, "MOUNTAIN DWARF", INVISIBILITY, STRENGTH, ULTRAVISION, INNATE

