"GOD, LIGHTNING"
===========================================================================
&+mSyntax: lightning <victim>&n

&+mThis god social lets you strike your hapless victim with lightning. Ka-ZAP!&n
===========================================================================

#
"GOD, LOAD"
===========================================================================
&+mFor loading new objects or characters from the database. The format is:&n

&+m     load <type> <number>&n

&+mwhere <type> is either 'obj' or 'char', and number is the v-number of the&n
&+mobject or character you wish to create.&n

&+mExample: load o 1400&n
===========================================================================
See also: "GOD, LOOKUP"

#
"GOD, LOOKUP"
===========================================================================
&+m"Lookup" is for finding the database number (v-number) of objects or&n
&+mcharacters in preparation for loading or statting.&n

&+mSyntax : lookup <room | zone | mob | obj> <pattern>&n

&+mExample: lookup o staff&n

&+mGives you a listing of all items with staff in their short description&n
&+malong with their associated database number.&n
===========================================================================
See also: "GOD, LOAD", "GOD, STAT"

#
"GOD, PARDON"
===========================================================================
"Pardon" will remove the OUTLAW flag.&n
===========================================================================
See also: "GOD, PFLAGS", "GOD, SETBIT"

#
"GOD, PARTICIPATION"
===========================================================================
&+mThis refers to the level to participation each god is expected to&n
&+mcontribute to the MUD. In order to obtain and maintain a god of some power&n
&+mhere on Duris, each god is expected to continually contribute in some&n
&+mfashion.&n

&+mThe point the Forgers are trying to make is that it is a *privilege* to be&n
&+ma god here on Duris, not a right. Once you have earned your immortality,&n
&+myou are an example to all others below you, mortal or immortal, and there&n
&+mwill always be others that, given the chance, would gladly take your&n
&+mposition.&n

&+mYou are expected to contribute to the MUD in some fashion and on a regular&n
&+mbasis. Unlike some MUDs, you cannot create one or two zones, earn a god,&n
&+mand ride on fame forever. We do NOT, however, mean that you have to work&n
&+mevery day (or even every month), but *some* type of contribution from every&n
&+mgod is necessary to keep Duris expanding and growing.&n

&+mAll gods will be assessed on a regular basis and assessments will be&n
&+mhandled in this manner:&n
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
&+mEach month, during the Forgers' regular meeting, each god (including&n
&+mforgers) will be evaluated for the month based on what they have done or&n
&+mnot done to contribute to the MUD. One month of inactivity is fine, even&n
&+mtwo, if you are busy, but *not* three. If you have a reason, such as school&n
&+mor something that inhibits you, fine. If you are having trouble to the&n
&+mextent that it will drastically affect your MUD contribution, inform the&n
&+mForgers *immediately* and there will be no hassles whatsoever.&n

&+mBear in mind that gods with months of inactivity (without a plausible&n
&+mexcuse) will be demoted to mortal status. There will always be other people&n
&+mwho wish to work for Duris and help us out. Inactive gods can easily be&n
&+mreplaced.&n

&+mThe god slots are limited. Thus, if you wish to keep your god, you will&n
&+mhave to work for it like the rest of us (including Forgers).&n

&+mRemember, it is a privilege to be a god here, not a right.&n
===========================================================================

#
"GOD, PFLAGS"
===========================================================================
"Pflags" lets you toggle flags for players.  Current flags:  OUTLAW.
There may be more in the future.
===========================================================================

#
"GOD, POOFIN" "GOD, POOFOUT"
===========================================================================
"poofin <text>" sets up the message for when you "goto" a room. This
replaces the default "ear-splitting bang" message we are used to seeing. To
get the default back, just type poofin with no argument.

"Poofout" is the same as poofin, except is is the message seen by people in
the room you are leaving when you do a "goto."

To see what your current poofin/-out is, type "poofin ?" or "poofout?"
===========================================================================
See also: "GOD, GOTO"

#
"GOD, PTELL"
===========================================================================
Syntax:  ptell <player> <text>

This is exactly like tell, except that <text> is broadcast to all gods
with petition toggled on, to let them know that you responded to a
particular petition.

Example:
        Oinkoink petitions 'Why is the sky blue?'

You reply:
        ptell oinkoink shut the hell up before I term you!

Which displays to the gods as:
        Petition: <your_name> responds to Oinkoink's petition with
        'shut the hell up before I term you!'
==========================================================================

#
"GOD, PURGE"
===========================================================================
"Purge" is a way to make the world a little cleaner.

Syntax:
  purge                To empty the room of all monsters and TAKEable objects
  purge <character>    To remove a living thing.  Kicks out a player.
  purge <object>       Removes an object, TAKEable or not.

Note: purging a container will also remove everything in it, whereas
purging a character will make their equipment drop to the ground.
===========================================================================

#
"GOD, REINITPHYS"
===========================================================================
Syntax:  reinitphys <player>

This command rerolls a player's height and weight.
===========================================================================

#
"GOD, RELEASE"
===========================================================================
Syntax:  release <socket_number>

This releases a given socket and the corresponding character's
connection.
===========================================================================
See also: "GOD, BAN", "GOD, ALLOW", "GOD, USERS"

#
"GOD, RESTORE"
===========================================================================
When used on a mortal, "restore" restores their hit points, mana, and
movement points to full.

When used on an immortal, "restore" also resets various fields to
their proper values.

Immortals should take cautionary measures if they decide to restore a
player, as this is normally frowned upon.

Syntax:  restore <character>
===========================================================================

#
"GOD, SECRET"
===========================================================================
Syntax:  secret <object>

This command sets the SECRET bit on an object.
===========================================================================
See also: SEARCH

#
"GOD, SETATTR"
===========================================================================
"Setattr" is used to set various attributes of a player.  Type in
command "setattr" with no arguments for a list of settable attributes.

Example:
  > setattr fizzwig wis 18
===========================================================================
See also: "GOD, SETBIT"

#
"GOD, SETBIT"
===========================================================================
"Setbit" lets you set a variety of fields in rooms, doors, zones,
objects, or characters.  Be extremely careful in its usage.

Syntax:

setbit room room-number flag-type value [on|off]
setbit char name flag-type value [on|off]
setbit obj  name flag-type value [on|off]
setbit dir  room-number flag-type value [on|off]
setbit aff  name[aff-number] flag value [on|off]
===========================================================================
See also: "GOD, PFLAGS", "GOD, SETATTR"

#
"GOD, SETHOME"
===========================================================================
"Sethome" lets you set a character's hometown and birthplace.

Syntax:

sethome <char> <birthplace/hometown> <room>
===========================================================================

#
"GOD, SILENCE"
===========================================================================
"Silence" lets you clamp down on an annoying player's communication
skills.  They can neither shout nor hear shouting nor petition.
Silence the player again to remove the SILENCE flag.

Syntax:  silence <player>
===========================================================================

#
"GOD, SNOOP"
===========================================================================
Syntax:  snoop <victim>

This command lets you see everything that the MUD sends to the
victim's screen, except for the prompt.  It is not possible to snoop
someone of equal or higher level.

Note: snooping is to be used only for clearing up problems, and not for
intruding on people's affairs. Excessive snooping is strongly frowned upon.
===========================================================================

#
"GOD, SNOWBALL"
===========================================================================
Syntax:  snowball <victim>

This god social action lets you magically conjure a snowball and throw
it in your victim's face.
===========================================================================

#
"GOD, SPELLS"
===========================================================================
Syntax:  spells

This command gives you a comprehensive listing of all skills, spells,
songs, etc.
===========================================================================

#
"GOD, STAT"
===========================================================================
"Stat" reveals information about rooms, zones, objects, and
characters.

Syntax:
   stat room <room #>
   stat zone <zone #>
   stat char|mob #|'name'
   stat obj|item  #|'name'

Do not reveal stats to mortals.  This is punishable by deletion.
===========================================================================
See also: "GOD, LOOKUP"

#
"GOD, STRING"
===========================================================================
"String" is for changing the text-strings associated with objects and
characters.

Syntax:  string <type> <name> <field> [<string> | <keyword>]

<type> is either <obj> or <char>

<field> is one of the following (the names may be abbreviated):

Name                    (the call-name of an obj/char -e.g., "giant")
Short                   (for inventory lists (obj's) and actions (char's))
Long                    (for when obj/character is seen in room)
Title                   (for players)
Description             (for look-at.  For obj's, must be followed by
                         a keyword)
Delete-description      (only for obj's.  Must be followed by a keyword)

Where a string is expected as the last argument, a newline will make
you enter a string mode (like a bulletin board), and the game will
prompt you for new lines to the string until you exceed the maximum
length for the string or you end a line with a '@'.
===========================================================================&
See also: "GOD, TITLE"

#
"GOD, SUPERVISE"
===========================================================================
Syntax: supervise guild <guild number>

This lets you control a guild above and beyond its mortal leaders,
as well as listen to their GCC chat. For a complete guild listing, use
"asclist".
===========================================================================

#
"GOD, SWITCH" "GOD, RETURN"
===========================================================================
Syntax:  switch <mob>

This lets you move your god's mind into the body of a mob, directing
its actions until you type "return."  Note that you will be restricted
by many of the restrictions on the mob, particularly speech.
===========================================================================

#
"GOD, TELEPORT"
===========================================================================
Syntax:  teleport <victim> <room # | character>

This command changes the room of the victim to the desired location or
the location of <character>.
===========================================================================
See also: "GOD, GOTO", "GOD, TRANS"

#
"GOD, TITLE"
===========================================================================
Syntax:  title <character> <title_text>

This command lets you retitle a character.  We currently only allow
titles to gods or characters in guilds (or very rarely, characters who
have proved their worth as adventurers).
===========================================================================

#
"GOD, TRANS"
===========================================================================
Syntax:  trans <victim>

This lets you bring the victim into your current room.

Note:  unless you are very high level, you cannot bring victims into
places they could not go on their own, such as ocean rooms.
===========================================================================
See also: "GOD, GOTO", "GOD, TRANS"

#
"GOD, USERS"
===========================================================================
Syntax:  users [<victim>]

Without an argument, this gives you a complete list of users, their
socket, idle time, room, and connection site, and connection status.

With an argument, it gives you the same information but for just the
single user.

Do NOT reveal users' sites to other mortals.
===========================================================================
See also: "GOD, BAN", "GOD, ALLOW", "GOD, RELEASE"

#
"GOD, VIS"
===========================================================================
"vis" makes you invisible to other players with levels below a certain
limit.

Example:
  > vis         : Returns current minimum visibility level.
  > vis 10      : Sets minimum visibility level so that players with
                  levels <=10 cannot see you.
===========================================================================
See also: DISPLAY, VIS

#
"GOD, WHERE"
===========================================================================
This will tell you the detailed location of all things (monsters, players,
objects) with a given name.

Examples:
  where dragon
  where fizzwig
  where torch

You can also type "where" without arguments to see where all visible
players are.
===========================================================================

#
"GOD, WIZHELP"
==========================================================================
This lists the privileged (i.e., god-only) commands available to you.
===========================================================================

#
"GOD, WIZLOCK"
===========================================================================
Syntax:  wizlock create
         wizlock connection
         wizlock maxplayers <limit>

This locks the game so that no new players can be created.
===========================================================================

#
"GOD, WIZMSG"
===========================================================================
Syntax:  wizmsg [<level>] <text>

With no level arguments, it will deliver a message to all the gods. This
command will also allow you to specify the minimum level of god who can
hear your message. Currently <level> cannot go below the lowest god level
or above the highest one.
===========================================================================

#
GRAB HOLD (General Information)
===========================================================================
Syntax:  grab <object> | hold <object>

For holding or getting a good grip on something:  a torch, for
example.
===========================================================================
See also: WEAR, WIELD, REMOVE, INVENTORY, EQUIPMENT

#
GRANT (General Information)
===========================================================================
Syntax: grant list 
        grant add <name> 
        grant rem <name> 

Grant enables you to let other people access your personal storage locker. 
To view your list, type 'grant list'. You can add or remove people on the 
list, which will be saved. Be careful who you allow to access your storage!
Please note that the grant command is used within your locker itself. 
===========================================================================
See also: LOCKER, STORAGE

#
GRAPPLE
===========================================================================
With their heightened battle senses, the Ragelord is more able to take
advantage of their opponents misadventure. Watching closely for failures
in takedown maneuvers they grab the opportunity in the situation and slam
their foe bodily to the ground, leaving them momentarily unable to respond.
===========================================================================
See also: "HAMMER MASTERY", RAGELORD, BERSERKER, SKILL_BERSERKER

