#
NEWBIE (General Information)
===========================================================================
The term "newbie" is given to a player who is new to the MUD or to MUDding
in general. If you fit this category, we suggest that you spend some time
reading the help files. This will allow you to enter the game and play with
some degree of confidence.

Newbies are encouraged to ask questions of their fellow adventurers often,
to group for protection and to read thoroughly the HELP and INFO files for
information on the MUD.

MUD is an acronym for "multi-user dungeon".  Although there are different
types of MUDs all over the world, Duris runs on modified UBC code and is
loosely based on the Forgotten Realms series of AD&D (Advanced Dungeons and
Dragons) products from TSR, Inc.

NEWBIE TIPS:
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
If you are new to Duris and the Duris style of MUDding, there are some tips
you can follow that can help you get better oriented and give you more
control over the way you see the world.

First and most importantly, Duris can be a very difficult world, and if you
are not an advanced player it is HIGHLY recommended you play a good raced
character rather than an evil one. Evils face many hardships of various
kinds, and in general evils do not take kindly upon strangers.

Some commands that will help you further: 

&+W1. READ 'HELP COMMANDS'&n. 
This will list all the basic commands you will need to act and interact 
within the MUD. Spend time experimenting with the commands until you feel 
confident using them.

&+W2. TOGGLES&n. 
Typing 'toggle' will give you a list of personal settings you can switch 
on and off for your character. These toggles affect elements such as what 
your character sees, how it communicates, how it behaves in combat and 
much more. Make sure you read 'HELP TOGGLE' for more in-depth info mation 
on individual toggles.

&+W3. DISPLAY&n. 
Typing 'help display' will give you a list of display commands. Experiment 
with these commands until you are familiar with how each one affects what 
you see while playing. After your character first enters the game, we 
strongly recommend typing 'DISPLAY ALL'. This should make things easier on 
you.

If you require any further help, ask your fellow adventurers or check out
the Duris website. Try to group with those near your level to do experience, 
if you are a good raced character you are able to use "nchat" (newbie chat 
channel) to ask questions, or petition a god for help if you're truly lost.
===========================================================================
See also: TOGGLE, DISPLAY, COMMANDS, WEBSITE, FORUMS, INDEX, NCHAT

#
NEW-COMBAT "NEW COMBAT" "GROUP RANKS" RANKS "FRONT RANK" "BACK RANK"
===========================================================================
The biggest, most important change with the new combat stuff is the
new, increased importance of group ranks.  Group ranking is now critical
to the success of PvP engagements.

As before, there are two group ranks ... front and back.  However, the
old effects of group ranking are no longer.

  *)  You must have, at all times, more people in the front rank of your
      group than in the back rank.  The code will enforce this for the
      most part, though there will be times (especially when someone dies
      or leaves the room) when it won't immediately be updated.

  *)  If you are in the rear rank, leave the room, and come back in, as with
      a flee/return combo, you will automatically be ranked to the front.

  *)  Targeted spells can be targeted by anyone on anyone, regardless of
      which group rank the caster and target are in.

  *)  Area spells are still in the game, with a few modifications:
	-Casting time has been increased for all areas
	-Area spells do significantly less damage than before
	-Area spells hit ALL ranks in front of you.  This means if you are
	  grouped to the back rank, you will hit your front rank as well as
	  both enemy ranks.  If you are ranked front, you will hit only the
	  enemy group.

  *)  People in the rear ranks are much harder to target with physical
      attacks. 

The general theory behind this change is to change battles from the current
area spam-fests to battles that require thought and skill to win.  Clearly a
basic group format will have tanks and hitters in the front ranks, with clerics
and other casters in the rear ranks.  However, experimentation with various
group formats will be critical to success.  There will also be no single one
size fits all solution that guarantees a win ... you will have to be flexible
and above all, you have to use your brain, especially with who the primary
targets will be for both casters as well as hitters.

Remember, once you kill one of the front ranked people, one of the rear ranked
guys moves forward (assuming equal numbers in front and back)

I'll leave it up to you folks to see how mob combat will be affected by these
changes.

Expect damages, spell chant times, and just about any other facet of this to
be tweaked as it's used.  Of great use to me will be battle logs that show
problems you may run across.  
===========================================================================

