#
ROUNDKICK (Skill)
===========================================================================
Syntax:         Roundkick <victim>
Aggressive:     Yes

Roundkick is a martial arts skill where the attacker spins around on one
foot and strikes out at their enemy with the other. A well-placed roundkick
damages its victim, possibly stunning him. A badly failed roundkick will
send the attacker crashing to the ground.
===========================================================================

#
SACK (General Information)
===========================================================================
Sacking is conquering a guildhall and claiming as your own. To sack a
guildhall, you must get passed the golems by killing them. You must remain
in the hall, alive, for one week game time. If you die, or leave the hall
at any time, your sack with be nullified. 

Once a guildhall has been sacked, all golems and teleporter objects will
be removed or inactive. The new owning guild may then start building new
golems and other items.

You must be 25th level minimum to sack a guildhall.
===========================================================================

#
"SAFE FALL" (Skill)
===========================================================================
Safe Fall is a skill granted to rogues and all rogue types. When skilled at
it, the falling victim can fall for a distance and not sustain significant
damage when hitting the ground.
===========================================================================

#
SAVE (Command)
===========================================================================
Syntax:         save

The "Save" command allows you to save the current state of your character.
This includes experience points, statistics, money and equipment. If the 
game crashes, it resets your character to the statistics and equipment it 
had the last time you saved. It is a good idea to manually save your 
character often, especially if you have recently leveled, potioned or 
fragged. Your character is autosaved periodically by the MUD itself, but 
this is a timed event and may not pick up your more recent changes.
===========================================================================
See also: "TOGGLE_SAVE NOTIFY", CRASH

#
"SAVING THROW" "SAVING THROWS"
===========================================================================
A saving throw is a measure of your ability to withstand certain forms of
attack. Every player in the game, monsters included, has five different
saving throw values. These values are level-dependent. The five different
values are as follows:

        SPE     Save versus Spells.
        PAR     Save versus Paralyzation.
        BRE     Save versus Breath Weapon.
        FEA     Save versus Petrification/Polymorph.
        ROD     Save versus Rod/Staff/Wand.

Each of the saving throws has a value from 0 to 20.  The higher your saving
throw, the worse off you are. But what do the numbers mean?

Let's say you are in combat with a red dragon and the dragon breathes fire
at you. In this example, let's say your saving throw vs. breath weapon
(BRE) is 10. A random 20-sided die roll is made when the dragon breathes at
you. If the value of the roll is 11 or above, you have successfully saved
vs. the dragon's breath, and take only half damage from it. If the roll is
0-10, you have failed your save and will take full damage from the dragon's
fire. Thus, the lower the saving throw you have, the greater your chances
are for saving against the dragon's breath.

The same system works for spells. If, for example, a player-killer arrives
and tries to cast a "sleep" spell on you, and you fail your save, you will
be affected and fall asleep. If you save successfully, you will be
unaffected.

Normally, saving throws are determined by the experience your character has
achieved and they will get steadily smaller as you go up in level. There
are, however, items in the game that will lower your saving throws
magically.
===========================================================================

#
SAY TELL WHISPER ASK (Command)
===========================================================================
Syntax:         say <text> &+G-or-&n ' <text>
                tell <character> <text>
                whisper <character> <text>
                ask <character> <text>

In order to communicate with other players, you must begin your sentences 
with one of the above commands. Use "Say" if you wish everyone in the room 
to hear you (characters who are asleep are incommunicado, except to gods).  
The single character ' is a shortcut for "Say" and has precisely the same 
syntax. "Tell", "Whisper" and "Ask" are used to keep your conversations
private and must be accompanied by the name of the player with whom you wish 
to converse. "Whisper" and "Ask" can only be used if the player you want to 
converse with is the same room. Whereas, "Tell" is used for global 
communication. You can "Tell" anyone who is awake and has the tell toggle
ON, no matter where they are in the MUD.

Toggling "Tell" will effectively allow you to turn off this line of 
communication. However, it will not prevent a God from speaking to you.
===========================================================================
See also: TOGGLE, TOGGLE_TELL

#
