SHIP SHIPS
===========================================================================

Table of Contents for Ships -Type "Help <Ship_category>" to view
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
  SHIP_BASIC      -Buying a ship and preparing to go to sea
  SHIP_LIST       -The "List" command when at a docks
  SHIP_MOVEMENT   -Moving around in the docks and on the world
  SHIP_COMBAT     -Almost everything you need to know about combat
  SHIP_CARGO      -Almost everything you need to know about running cargo
  SHIP_LOOKS      -All the different ways to "look around"
  SHIP_COMMANDS   -A thorough list of all ship commands
  SHIP_CREWS      -Some extra information about crews

===========================================================================

#
SHIP_BASIC
===========================================================================
A dock is much like any other shop, you use "buy #" and "list" to see what 
ships and ship accessories are available at the docks.  You can only buy 
a ship at one of the major docks in the world.  An example is Tharnadia on 
the Goodie Continent.  To buy your first ship, you must also give it a name. 
Names of ship use ANSI commands so you should first use "Testcolor" command 
to perfect the name of your ship, otherwise you could end up with a lousy 
looking shipname.

The syntax for buying your first ship is "buy # <shipname>" where # is 
the number of the hull you wish to purchase, and shipname is the above 
mentioned name you create using ANSI commands. 

Ok, now you've purchased your ship, the "list" menu at all docks will 
have changed.  You can now see 4 sections instead of just one. From now 
on, you will not have to state a shipname when you buy or upgrade your 
hull.  You are PERMANENTLY stuck with that shipname for this character. 

Next suggested reading: "help SHIP_LIST" 

===========================================================================
See also: ANSI, TESTCOLOR, SHIP_LIST, SHIPS

#
SHIP_CREWS
===========================================================================
In Sarmiz'Duul, you will find a pub that has several crews for hire.

Syntax:
hire <number> <sail/gun>

-==Sail Crews==-
Standard Crew        Repair Rating:20      Cost: Free (starting crew)
Veteran Crew         Repair Rating:30      Cost: 2000 platinum
Elite Crew           Repair Rating:40      Cost: 5000 platinum
Repair Crew          Repair Rating:70      Cost: 750 platinum
-==Gun Crews==-
Standard Crew        Stamina:70            Cost: Free (starting crew)
Veteran Archers      Stamina:100           Cost: 2000 platinum
Elite Catapult Crew  Stamina:130           Cost: 5000 platinum
Stamina Crew         Stamina:200           Cost: 750 platinum

Veteran crews (of both types) require 500 ship frags to purchase.
Elite crews require 1000 ship frags to purchase.

It is rumored that an expert machinist has perfected the construction of
Automoton crews, but most believe this to be just a rumor.
Under the &+Yremote&n possibility it &+Ywere&n true, it would require an &+RINSANE&n
number of ship frags for him to even &+Yconsider&n selling you the crews.

Each crew has an experience level that looks like this:  5/10
The lower number is how much exp your crew currently has, and the higher
number is the max exp that crew can achieve.

If your ship frags drops below the amount needed to purchase that crew
you will lose that crew.

At the moment, experience is a reflection of your ship frags:
200 ship frags = 2 experience.
500 ship frags = 5 experience.

===========================================================================
See also: SHIPS

#
SHIP_LIST
===========================================================================
This is one of few single commands that will be covered in a helpfile, 
simply because this command holds so much information. When you type 
"list" at a dock, after you have purchased a ship, you see 4 sections: 

-Hull Upgrades 
-Sail 
-Weapons 
-and then a set of sample commands. 


Hull Upgrades
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
This section tells you all the larger ship classes you can upgrade your 
current ship to. A portion of the cost of your current hull will be 
deducted from the cost of upgrading to a higher hull class. This means, 
if you buy a sloop, and then a clipper, it will be more expensive than 
simply buying a clipper to start with. However, it will not be as costly 
as buying two separate ships (the clipper and the sloop). Again, you will 
not need to restate the name of your ship, when you upgrade your hull. 

Sail
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
Your ship requires a sail to move (sorry, you cannot move a galleon by 
paddling it with your hands). Sails are free, but depending on the size of 
the sail, it can take a long time to make the sail and put it on the ship. 
If you do not have enough sail, your ship is immobile (your sail isn't very 
effective with big holes in it). Likewise, if your sail is damaged, you 
will move slower and slower until you are also immobile. 

Weapons
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
Weapons are the fun part of sailing. Shooting down other players and 
their ships! Combat will be covered in "Help SHIP_COMBAT." When you buy a
weapon, you must state what part of the ship the weapon should be mounted
on. You should read "Help SHIP_COMBAT" before you buy weapons, so you can
develop your fighting strategy and buy your weapons to match. To buy a
weapon, you type "buy weapon # <location>" where # is the weapon ID number
when you type "list" at the docks, and location is the part of the ship you
wish to place the weapon. 

At the moment, capitol weapons require 2000 ship frags to purchase.

Finally, the commands list at the bottom of the "list" command output a few 
commands on how to operate the buying, selling, repairing, reloading, etc. 
of your ship. There is also a line "Available space on ship:" which tells 
you how much space you have to purchase more cargo, sail, or weapons. The 
higher the ship class, generally means you have more room for each of these 
items. 

Next suggested reading: "help SHIP_MOVEMENT" 

===========================================================================
See also: SHIP_COMBAT, SHIP_COMMANDS, SHIPS

#
SHIP_MOVEMENT
===========================================================================
Once you have purchased your ship and sail, you are ready to sail the seas,
pillage ships, run cargo, and travel the world. 

Dock Movement
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
When you are docked, you cannot unfurl your sails and take off safely. 
You must first maneuver out to the open seas, away from the docks. Some 
docks have complex zones, much like a normal zone, except it's all water. 
You still maneuver in "rooms" dictating N,S,E, or W as the direction. 

The command to maneuver is: "Order Maneuver <direction>" 

World Movement
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
The ship system works on a principle of speed and heading. What this means
is, if you set your ship to a certain speed, it will continue moving until
the speed is set to 0. Heading is the direction that the ship is pointing
and hence will be the direction the ship will be traveling. Heading is
done from a 0-360 degree circle with north being 0, east being 90, south 
being 180, and west being 270. 

Also affecting the ships is acceleration and turn rate. When a speed is 
set, the ship does not immediately jump to that speed, it has to accelerate 
to the set speed. Acceleration is faster on smaller ships with large sails 
than a large ship with small sails. On the same note, when a heading is 
set, the ship does not immediately face that direction, it has to turn to 
indicated direction, this is the turn rate. Turn rate is higher on smaller 
ships than large Dreadnaughts, so theoretically a small fast Clipper can 
run circles around a Galleon. Turn rate is also affected by the speed of 
the ship, the faster a ship is traveling the slower they turn, and below a 
minimum speed, the ship also turns slower so it is best to maintain a 
medium speed for best maneuverability. 

Details
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
In order to re-dock your ship, you must be adjacent to the dock zone, or 
adjacent to an area of land which is dockable [Note-1], and you again use 
the "order maneuver <direction>" command as you use when you are leaving 
the docks. Beware: if you attempt to SAIL into a shore, you have a chance 
of CRASHING into the shore, even if the zone is a dock. Your ship crew 
will try to prevent this, but they cannot be relied upon every time.  You 
must also be traveling at 20 speed or less in order to attempt to maneuver. 

Next suggested reading: "help Ship_Combat" 

NOTE:  Such as shores and coasts. Not all shores and coasts are dockable 
You are expected to find these other locations yourself, however if another
ship is already docked there, this is a good indicator. To test a spot,
simply sail alongside the square, slow to 10 speed or less, and attempt to
maneuver onto the shore. If it works, you found it, if not, DON'T CRASH! :) 
         
===========================================================================
See also: SHIP_COMMNDS, SHIPS

#
SHIP_COMBAT SHIP_BATTLE 
===========================================================================
Combat on the ship system works on the principle of firing arcs, range, 
targets, and damage. 

Firing Arcs
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
Firing arcs are the direction your weapons are pointing on your ship. For 
example, a ballistae mounted on your Port(Left) side is pointing to the 
ship's left, so if the target is on the right side, it is out of that 
particular weapon's arc, so if weapons are mounted only on the forward arc, 
that means the ship only has a limited arc of fire in the front. If a ship 
has weapons on all four parts of the ship it can shoot in any direction. 

Range
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
Each weapon has a Short, Medium, and Long range to them. What this means 
is that a Large Ballistae which might have a Short range of 4, Medium of 
8, and long of 12 can shoot targets as far as 12 squares away, as the ship 
gets closer to the target and gets within 8 squares, the ship will have a 
better chance of hitting the target, if the target gets within 4 squares, 
it will be an almost sure hit. 

Targets
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
Fighting in ships requires you to lock onto another ship. This uses the 
ID of the ship (covered in "help Ship_Looks"). The syntax is "Lock <ID>" 
When you are locked onto a ship, your crew will try to attack that ship and 
only that ship when you order them to fire weapons. However, you can 
reassign the Lock id at any time, as often and as quickly as you wish. 

Damage
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
When a ship is hit, it is hit on one of the four sides. Each side has 
two types of HP, armor and hull. Armor is made to take damage, as long as 
a ship has armor, its weapons and insides are protected. Once the ship's 
armor is blasted away however, damage goes to the hull of the ship. Hull 
is basically the framework of the ship, hits in the hull can cause critical 
hits where it knocks the crew to the ground or even destroys weapons. Once 
all the hull of a side is gone, the ship is taking on water, not enough to 
sink it, but enough to immobilize it. Once two hull sides are blown away, 
the ship no longer can float and will sink. If the ship is fast enough and 
doesn't want to get blown up, they have the choice of running, but be 
warned, the rear of a ship has about half the armor and has more delicate 
structure than the rest of the ship (Like the Rudder) so the ship will be 
quite vulnerable there. Also when a ship gets hit, it has a chance of 
getting hit in the sails which makes the ship not able to move as fast 
(can't move if your sails have big holes in it), and even possibly, with 
enough hits, the sail can get completely destroyed, making the ship 
immobile, or basically dead in the water -a sitting duck. 

Next suggested reading: "help SHIP_CARGO" 
If you don't like cargo: "help SHIP_LOOKS" 

Note: When a weapon is fired it will take approx 30 seconds to reload. 

Note: As a last resort you can RAM the other ship, which does massive 
damage to both.
Syntax:  Order Ram
You need to be moving fast for this to work.

Note: Many players will disembark their own ship after they immobilize 
yours, and then board yours to kill you AND your destroy your ship 
afterwards. You can also do this yourself (just don't die on THEIR ship).

After Sinking a ship, use the command "Get Money" to collect the prize
money for sinking your enemy.

===========================================================================
See also: SHIP_LOOKS, SHIP_COMMANDS, SHIPS

#
SHIP_CARGO 
===========================================================================

Space
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
Cargo takes up 1 unit of space on your ship. Sails take up 3 units of 
space, and each weapon takes up it's specific labeled amount of space. Type 
"list" to see how much space a weapon takes up. For every unit of cargo 
you are hauling, your ACTUAL top speed becomes 2 less than your LISTED top 
speed. This occurs ONLY if your ship is completely full(0 space remaining) 
This means if you are hauling 15 cargo, your actual top speed is 30 less 
than your listed top speed. You can still set your speed above this value, 
but your ship will not actually go that speed. See "Help SHIP_LOOKS" to 
see how to determine your current speed. Bigger ships have more space. 

Buying and Selling
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
To buy cargo, go to one of the major docks in the world, and dock your 
ship there. Then type "list cargo". This gives you a list of the one type 
of cargo you can BUY at this dock, and the many other types of cargo you 
can SELL here. It also gives you a list of prices, which are vital to 
actually MAKING MONEY, which is the sole purpose of running cargo. Make 
sure you buy low and sell high. First determine how much space you have 
or need to make for cargo. A few methods of cargo running are: 

Minimum cargo, Maximum speed 
     (tune your ship to carry only enough cargo to travel 60-90) 
Half and half 
     (tune your ship to travel about 40-70 when hauling cargo) 
Maximum cargo, Minimum speed 
     (tune your ship to barely any sails or speed, but once you get there, 
      you'll be RICH -this is very hard without weapons -which take up 
      valuable cargo space) 

Finally, to buy cargo, stand on the dock, and type "buy cargo #" where # is 
the number of units of cargo you wish to buy. 

Once you buy the cargo, you sail to a DIFFERENT major dock.  Disembark, and 
type "sell cargo". You should type "list cargo" to ensure you're making a 
profit first. 

Then, repeat, buy, sail somewhere, sell.... 

Next suggested reading: "help SHIP_LOOKS" 

Note: If you summon your ship to another location, all cargo in your ship 
will be lost. Use summon only as a last resort if you run cargo. 

Note: Each major docks has it's own type of cargo. This should never 
change. Therefore, by number of types of cargo available, you can determine
how many major ports there are, and even approximate what continent any
specific type of cargo can be purchased at. Example: Elven Goods are bought
on the Elven Continent. 

Note: A sloop and a Yacht have limited space. Those two ships can have 100%
sail, so you have to buy LESS than the max sail to haul cargo, at 3 sail
taking the same space as 1 cargo. 

Note: Many cargo ships have no weapons. If you are attacked, and you 
Would rather live and escape than sink to the bottom of the ocean, you can
type "order jettison cargo" and your actual top speed will now match your
listed top speed, allowing you to escape. 

===========================================================================
See also: SHIP_COMMANDS, SHIPS

#
SHIP_COMMANDS DISEMBARK REPAIR RELOAD
===========================================================================
Key to symbols:
  {}         One time only parameter
  []         Optional parameter
  <>         Required parameter
  *          Number
  <D>        Direction
  <F/R/P/S>  Required parameter, Ship location (Fore/Rear/Port/Starboard)

Commands at a Dock (Most of these only at a Main dock)
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
List
List Cargo
Summon Ship -only main docks in a ZONE
Buy <*> {Name in ANSI} -for buying ship or upgrading ship
Buy Sail <*>
Buy Weapon <*> <F/R/P/S>
Buy Cargo <*>
Sell Cargo
Repair <armor/internal/sail/weapon> <F/R/P/S/All>
Reload <Weapon */All>
Enter *.ship -or-Enter <owner name> -or-Enter *.<shiptype>

Commands on a Ship
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
Order Undock
Order Maneuver <D>
Order Heading <*> or <D> -* is an angle measured clockwise from north
Order Speed <*>
Order Anchor
Order Ram

Look Out
Look Tactical [X] [Y]
Look Cargo
Look Status / Look Ship
Look Weaponspec
Look Sight <Weapon *>
Look Contacts
Look Crew

Lock <ID>
Lock off
Scan <ID>
Fire <Weapon *>
Frag Ship
Get Money
Disembark -only from the edge of a ship for large ships
===========================================================================
See also: SHIPS

#
SHIP_LOOKS 
===========================================================================

Look Out
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
This command looks outside your ship, at the immediate surroundings. If 
you are in a dock zone, it will tell you the available exits much like when 
you are walking around normally. This will tell you other ships in your 
square, and it will show you a small portion of the worldmap (in squares) 
when you are outside. 

Look Tactical
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
look tactical (optional parameters are <X> <Y>) 

This will show you a tactical map centered on you (or x,y with 50,50 
being the center of the map -ie YOU). It is displayed as a hex grid and 
any nearby ships will be displayed according to their ID. The Hex grid is 
the square setup basically "converted" to a hex grid, so it is not always 
perfect in appearance. If the optional parameters <X> and <Y> are given the
map will center on that coord if it is within 35 hexes. This is a
calculated value, if you provide numbers outside the range, you will see an
error message. You cannot Look Tactical inside a dock zone. 

Look cargo
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
This will tell you what cargo you currently have on your ship, and the 
price you paid for that cargo. 

Look Status/Look Ship
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
This will show you a detailed status of your ship with HPs and weapon 
status (whether its reloading or ready to fire) and ammo remaining. It 
will also show your position, speed, heading and target. The ID number on 
the upper right corner of the status display is your current ID if you are 
sailing, or a ** if you are docked. This ID starts at AA for the first 
ship out, and continues for as many ships are currently sailing. It can be 
an indicator of how many other ships are sailing the world, also. 

Look Weaponspec
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
This will show you the specifications of all your weapons. It will show 
their weapon ranges and damage each shot will do as well as if the weapon
is destroyed or not. 

Look Sight <#>
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
This will show your percent chance to hit with a specific weapon.

Look Sight <weapon number> 
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
If your have a target this command will show you your percentage to hit
the current locked target with that particular weapon. 

Look Contacts
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
This will display a list of all ships within a 35 square radius of your 
ship. This is the heart of getting info on your target. The list is broken 
into several parts and will look kinda like this:

Contact listing 
===============================================
[AN] 'NorgDog'         X:53  Y:50  Z:0   R:3.0   B:90  H:0   S:0 |S 

"AN" is the ship's ID this is the parameter you pass to lock to lock onto 
this target. 

'Norgdog' is the ship's name. 

X:53 and Y:50 are their x, y coords on your tactical map, so if you do a 
'look tactical 53 50', it will center the map on Norgdog. 

R:3.0 is Range, so in this case, Norgdog is 3 Squares from you. 

B:90 is their bearing to you, so in this case, Norgdog is to your east 
since 90 is east, so if you were to head east, you would be facing 
Norgdog. 

H:0 is Norgdog's heading.. so in this case, Norgdog is facing north 
since 0 is North. 

S:0 is Norgdog's speed so in this case, its not moving since it's 0. 

Last bit is the S, which means it is on your starboard firing 
arc, so if you have any weapons on your starboard side, they can fire at 
Norgdog. 

Next suggested reading: "help SHIP_COMMANDS" 

===========================================================================
See also: SHIP_COMMANDS, SHIPS

# 
"SHOCKING GRASP" (Spell)
===========================================================================
Area of effect: <victim>
Aggressive:     Yes
Cumulative:     No
Duration:       Instantaneous
Type of spell:  Electric

The spellcaster attempts to grasp the enemy with a bare hand, but for
only the briefest of instants. On contact, the victim is blasted with a 
searing shock of electricity, causing great pain.
===========================================================================

#
SHOPS SHOPKEEPER

Shops are places where players may purchase equipment for their
adventuring needs or sell extra items and treasures.  Many shops trade
only in specific types of merchandise, or may not have enough money to
pay you what your item's true value is.  Thus, a baker or an armorer
may refuse to buy your armor, even if it is of high quality!

To some people, murdering the keeper in the prospect of obtaining the
entire inventory of a shop, or gaining a large amount of experience
points may appear tempting, but beware!  Shopkeepers are often rugged,
capable men and women who are roughened by years of trading and
surviving in a harsh world.  Killing them may not be as easy as it
looks!

See also: BUY SELL, LIST, VALUE

#
SHOUT (Command)
===========================================================================
Syntax:         shout <text>
                toggle shout

"Shout" sends a message to all players within a certain range of you. If 
you are in a zone, the message will only be heard by those in that  
particular zone. If you are on the world map, the message will only be  
heard by those on that particular continent. In order to hear shouts, you 
must be conscious and have shout toggled on.
===========================================================================
See also: TOGGLE_SHOUT

#
SHREWTAMENESS (Spell)
===========================================================================
Area of effect: <victim>
Aggressive:     Yes
Cumulative:     No
Duration:       Dependent on proficiency of caster
Type of spell:  Animal

This spell decreases the victim's strength and damage-dealing ability,
causing him to be less of a threat to the caster.
===========================================================================
See also: LIONRAGE

#
SHRIEK (Innate)
===========================================================================
Area of effect: <victim>
Aggressive:     Yes
Cumulative:     No
Duration:       Instantaneous
Type of spell:  General

The astounding vocal range of a Disharmonist has given them the ability to
utilize their very voice as a weapon against their foe. The terrible 
shriek of the Disharmonist causes disturbing damage to the enemy despite
taking a toll on their throat, forcing them to rest for a period of time
before they can again strain their range to such a high limit.
===========================================================================
See also: DISHARMONIST, BARD

#
SIDESTEP (Skill)
===========================================================================
"Sidestep" is a reflexive skill that improves the mount's success at 
dodging attacks, with or without a rider. 
===========================================================================
See also: CAVALIER, "DEMONIC RIDER", DODGE

#
"SIGHT LINK" (Spell)
===========================================================================
Area of effect: <victim>
Aggressive:     No
Cumulative:     N/A
Duration:       Instantaneous
Type of spell:  Divination

"Sight Link" connects the minds of the caster and his victim, allowing
the caster to briefly see through the eyes of anyone, no matter where
they are.
===========================================================================

#
SILENCE (Spell)
===========================================================================
Area of effect: <victim>	
Aggressive:     Yes
Cumulative:     No
Duration:       Dependent on proficiency of caster
Type of spell:  Generic

When successful, the victim will be silenced, rendering them incapable of 
speaking or casting spells.
===========================================================================

#
"SIRENS SONG" (Spell)
===========================================================================
Area of effect: <victim>	
Aggressive:     Yes
Cumulative:     No
Duration:       Dependent on proficiency of caster
Type of spell:  Summoning

Upon casting, the druid emits a beautiful song that his target cannot
resist.  His intended victim will then unwittingly wander into the room,
following the music.
===========================================================================

#
SIZE
===========================================================================
Size is the average of height, length, diameter and weight of a creature.

The size are: None      : Almost no size
              Tiny      : 2' or less
              Small     : 2'+ to 4'
              Medium    : 4'+ to 7'
              Large     : 7'+ to 12'
              Huge      : 12'+ to 25'
              Giant     : 25'+ to 50'
              Gargantuan: 50'+

It has been rumored there are some spells in the game that can change the
size of a creature.
===========================================================================

#
SKEWER (Skill)
===========================================================================
Syntax:         bash <victim>

When bashing, there is a chance to "Skewer" the enemy. A successful
"Skewer" will inflict more damage than the average "Bash" and will keep the
opponent on the ground for a longer time.
===========================================================================
See also: BASH

#
SKILLS (General Information)
===========================================================================
Skills are methods of survival or battle tactics and techniques that are 
learned by classes through use over time. 

Your proficiency at a skill will increase over time if you apply the skill
as you adventure.

NOTE: Type "skill" to see a list of your character's skills are current
      proficiency at them.  
===========================================================================

